..</span><hr size=1> Here's an interesting article (click <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nationalpost.com/search/site/story.asp?id=15A4E0E4-09C8-4601-A3D3-E76EC1271EDE" target="top">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
<br>
Basically, it's a rising opinion that chipmakers need to pay more attention to costs than performance. This I agree with. Here's my thinking and how it relates to us and games like EQ, DAoC, Doom, etc.<br>
<br>
I go home and sit at my computer desk that houses my 2 computers, with a side station for my laptop. The computers I've built with my own two little (ok big) hands. One is an Athlon 1.2  and the other an Athlon XP1800+ Both have 1gig of ram, one with a G4 video card (overclocked) and the other with a g3 (not overclocked.) <br>
<br>
Today or tomorrow I'll have my watercooling kit in hand and the 1800+ system will be liquid cooled and overclocked.<br>
<br>
What's all that gibberish mean? Means I'm a DIYer. (Do It Yourself.)  Means I bought all the yahoos and doodads a piece at a time to build it. (Takes a whole hour or two.) Doing it yourself can save you 50%+ on the cost of your system. (Labor)<br>
<br>
Slowly, but on a more increasingly rapid pace, Intel and AMD (the two major chip builders) are pulling further and further away from the consumer market and investing their R &amp; D (research and development) into performance CPUs that are in the $600+ price range.<br>
<br>
Who here needs a P4 3.06 processor to play eq? An Athlon 3000+? Who has the $600 to throw away since the game won't perform any better on that machine than on an Athlon 1700+ with a good video card and adequate memory?<br>
<br>
These performance chips are aimed at the smallest and highest end of the market imo. Time to focus on bringing the price back in line with the larger share of the populace.<br>
