<br>
The real root of this is a business decision.  Intel and AMD can spend less on pushing out faster processors, but that results in resting on their laurels and not moving forward.  If they do that, they make more money now and spend less, but in a year they have less to offer the consumer who is now looking for what was once a high end 600 dollar part and is now a 200 dollar or less mid-range part.  Most businesses need to drive forward, especially if they have competition.  The technology increases in this case ( 90 nanometer processing and 64 bit processors) are also forced on them by being in competition with one another.  The price on those ultra high end components is high, but that's so they can recoup some decent money to start with from the early adopters.  At the same time it maintains the market viability of their current mid range product which would otherwise become instantly obsolete and no one would bother to buy it any more.  Each part has a target market, and it needs to be able to live up to that market long enough to be profitable.  Think of the cpu market like an ecosystem with the top priced parts being aimed at those placed in the top fo the food chain.<br>
<br>
